Some flags used here:

-e ;if true, the file exists
-f ;if true, it is a regular file
-d ;if true, it is a directory
-b ;if true, the file is block-special
-c ;if true, the file is character-special
-s ;if true, the file is not empty
-r ;if true, the file has read permission
-w ;if tru, the file has write permission
-x ;if true, the file has execute permission







fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ls
Bangladesh.txt  folder2  hello.sh

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ nano hello.sh
fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: Bangladesh.txt
Bangladesh.txt is found

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: file.txt
file.txt is not found

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ nano hello.sh
fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: Bangladesh.txt
Bangladesh.txt is found
It is a regular file

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ls
Bangladesh.txt  folder2  hello.sh
fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: hello.sh
hello.sh is found
It is a regular file

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: folder2
folder2 is found
It is not a regular file

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: folder2
folder2 is found
It is a directory

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ls -l newfile.txt
-rw-r--r-- 1 fokhrul fokhrul 0 Oct 16 00:26 newfile.txt
fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: newfile.txt
newfile.txt is found
It is a regular file
It is an empty file

fokhrul@fokhrul-VirtualBox:~/Desktop$ ./hello.sh
Enter the name of the file: folder2
folder2 is found
It is a directory
It is not empty




